Overview of a 5.2 Form

Topic Learning Outcome:

  1. Describe the general procedure for filing a Form 5.2.
  2. Recognize the different sections of a Form 5.2.

General Procedure

Click on the arrows to learn more about the general procedure for filing a Form 5.2.

When seizing property, with or without warrant, whether or not it is intended for an investigation, the seizing member shall complete a Form 5.2 with the necessary details, including the “Application for Detention.”

Subsequently, the form must be sent to a Justice of the Peace to ensure police return seized property as soon as practicable. The justice will complete the Detention Order For Things Seized, which authorizes the police, pursuant to section 490(1)(b) of the Criminal Code (1985), to retain the property for 90 days, from the date of seizure.

The seizing member shall submit the Form 5.2 - Report to Justice as an attachment to their General Occurrence report. The member should set themselves a diary date for 60 days from the date of seizure, to allow enough time to reassess their position on the property and seek further detention if required.

Sections of a Form 5.2

A Form 5.2 consists of 3 main sections.

Click on each icon to see an example of how each section should be filled.

Section 1

Section 1 of Form 5.2 shall be filled if a warrant to search has been issued.

Example of how Section 1 is to be filled.

Section 2

Section 2 of Form 5.2 shall be filled if no warrant has been issued.

Example of how Section 2 is to be filled.

Section 5

Section 3 of Form 5.2 must be completed with a description of items seized and where the item is detained or returned to. If more room is required, members shall continue the list using a form PCR 094 – Attachment to Report to a Justice. A PCR 094 is to be attached with a Form 5.2.

Example of how Section 3 is to be filled.

Example of how PCR 094 – Attachment to Report to a Justice is to be filled.
